window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>1","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"1","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : SEQUENCES AND SERIES","question":"The second term of a geometric progression is 3. If its sum to infinity is 25/2, find the value of the common ratio.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Second Term, T2 = 3  Sumtoinfinity,S\u221e=252  Common ratio, r = ?  Recall,  nth term of a GP, Tn = arn - 1  T2 = ar2 - 1  3 = ar  ar = 3 ------------ (i)  Recall,  S\u221e=a1 - r  252=a1 - r  25(1 - r) = 2a  25 - 25r = 2a  25 = 2a + 25r  2a + 25r = 25 --------------- (ii)  Solve simultaneously  From equation (i)  a=3r------------------(iii)  substitutea=3rintoequation(ii)  2(3r)+25r=25  multiply through by r  6 + 25r2 = 25r  25r2 - 25r + 6 = 0  Product: +150 } -15  Sum: -25 } -10  25r2 - 15r - 10r + 6 = 0  5r(5r - 3) - 2(5r - 3) = 0  (5r - 2)(5r - 3) = 0  5r - 2 = 0 or 5r - 3 = 0  5r = 2 or 5r = 3  r=25or35","marks":"10","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>2","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"2","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : SURDS","question":"Solve x2/3 - 5x1/3 + 6 = 0.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"x2/3 - 5x1/3 + 6 = 0  (x1/3)2 - 5(x1/3) + 6 = 0  Let a = x1/3  a2 - 5a + 6 = 0  Product: 6 } -3  Sum: -5 } -2  a2 - 3a - 2a + 6 = 0  a(a - 3) - 2(a - 3) = 0  (a - 3)(a - 2) = 0  a - 3 = 0 or a - 2 = 0  a = 3 or 2  Recall,  x1/3 = a    when a = 3  x1/3 = 3  x = 33  x = 27    when a = 2  x1/3 = 2  x = 23  x = 8  \u2234 x = 27 or 8","marks":"10","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>3","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"3","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : CO-ORDINATE GEOMETRY OF STRAIGHT LINES","question":"The normal to the curve y = 2x2 + x - 3 at the point (2, 7) meets the x-axis at point P. Find the coordinates of P.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"y = 2x2 + x - 3  Firstly, determine the gradient (m) of the curve at (2, 7)  m=dydx=4x+1  m = 4(2) + 1  m = 8 + 1 = 9  It should be noted that the normal is perpendicular to the tangent at (2, 7).  For two perpendicular lines,  m1m2 = -1  m1 = gradient of tangent to the curve at (2, 7)  m2 = gradient of normal to the curve at (2, 7)  9 \u00d7 m2 = -1  m2=-19  Since the curve cuts the x-axis, P is (x, 0).  Recall,  gradientofnormal,m=y2 - y1x2 - x  m=-19  (2, 7) \u21d2 x1 = 2, y1 = 7  (x, 0) \u21d2 x2 = x, y2 = 0  -19=0 - 7x - 2  -1(x - 2) = 9 \u00d7 -7  -x + 2 = -63  -x = -63 - 2  -x = -65  x = 65  Therefore the co-ordinate of P is (65, 0)","marks":"10","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>4>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : BINOMIAL THEOREM","question":"Write down the first four terms of the binomial expansion of (2 - 1/2x)5 in ascending powers of x.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"(2-12x)5  Since it has a positive power, pascal triangle can be used to determine the co-efficient of the expansion.    In the expansion, the power of 2 keeps decreasing while that of -1/2 x keeps increasing  (2+(-12x))5=1(2)5(-12x)0+5(2)4(-x2)1+10(2)3(-x2)2+10(2)2(-x2)3  =32+80(-x2)+80(x24)+40(-x38)  \u21d2 32 - 40x + 20x2 - 5x3","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>4>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : BINOMIAL THEOREM","question":"Use your expansion in (a) to find, correct to two decimal places, the value of (1.99)5.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"1.995 = (2 - 0.01)5  Equate  (2-12x)5=(2 - 0.01)5  2-x2=2-0.01  -x2=-0.01  x = 0.01 \u00d7 2  x = 0.02  substitute x = 0.02 into the expansion  \u21d2 32 - 40(0.02) + 20(0.02)2 - 5(0.02)3  \u21d2 31.20796  \u21d2 31.21 [2dp]","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>5>a>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"Five digit numbers are formed from digits 4, 5, 6, 7 and 8.    How many of such numbers can be formed if repetition of digits is allowed; ?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Available digits: 4, 5, 6, 7, 8  -  55555  Each box represents the number of digit that can occupy that position. Any of these digits can occupy each position. That is the reason for the 5 in each box.  \u21d2 5 \u00d7 5 \u00d7 5 \u00d7 5 \u00d7 5  \u21d2 3125 numbers","marks":"7.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>5>a>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"Five digit numbers are formed from digits 4, 5, 6, 7 and 8.  How many of such numbers can be formed if repetition of digits is not allowed?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Available digits: 4, 5, 6, 7, 8  -  54321  The first box can take any of the digits i.e 5 digits.  Any of the remaining four digits can occupy the second position after the first position has been occupied and so on.  \u21d2 5 \u00d7 4 \u00d7 3 \u00d7 2 \u00d7 1  \u21d2 120 numbers","marks":"7.5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>5>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"Five digit numbers are formed from digits 4, 5, 6, 7 and 8.    How many of the numbers are odd, if repetition of digits is not allowed?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"For the number to be odd, it must end with 5 or 7.  For a number ending with 5  43211  \u2191 &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp \u2191  Position&nbsp &nbsp Position for digit 5  for other   four digits  4 x 3 x 2 x 1  \u21d2 24 numbers    For a number ending with 7  43211  \u2191 &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp \u2191  Position&nbsp &nbsp Position for digit 5  for other   four digits  4 x 3 x 2 x 1  \u21d2 24 numbers    Total number = 24 + 24  \u21d2 48 numbers","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>6","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"6","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"Four boys participated in a competition in which their respective chances of winning prizes are 1/5, 1/4, 1/3 and 1/2. What is the probability that at most two of them win prizes?    Leave your answer in 3 decimal places 'a.bcd'*","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Let W, X, Y and Z represent the probabilities of the four boys winning.  W=15,X=14,Y=13,Z=12  Let Wn, Xn, Yn and Zn represent the probabilities of the four boys not winning.  Wn=1-15=45  Xn=1-14=34  Yn=1-13=23  Zn=1-12=12  The probability of at most 2 winning = two win or one wins or none wins  Two win = WXYnZn + WYXnZn + WZXnYn + XYWnZn + XZWnYn + YZWnXn  =15x14x23x12+15x13x34x12+15x12x34x23+14x13x45x14x12x45x23+13x12x45x34  =2120+3120+6120+4120+8120+12120  =35120  One wins = WXnYnZn + XWnYnZn + YWnXnZn + ZXnYnWn  =15x34x23x12+14x45x23x12+13x45x34x12+12x34x23x45  =6120+8120+12120+24120  =50120  None wins = WnXnYnZn  =45x34x23x12  =24120  =35120+50120+24120  =109120 \u223c0.908","marks":"10","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>7","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"7","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : STATICS","question":"Forces F1 = (10N, 090\u00b0), F2 = (20N, 210\u00b0) and F3 = (4N, 330\u00b0) act on a body at rest on a smooth table. Find, correct to one decimal place, the magnitude of the resultant force.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"F1 = (10N, 090\u00b0), F2 = (20N, 210\u00b0), F3 = (4N, 330\u00b0)    Resultant force, R = F1 + F2 + F3  R=10cos90\u00b010sin90+20cos210\u00b020sin210\u00b0+4cos330\u00b04sin330\u00b0  =010+-17.321-10+3.464-2  = 0 - 17.321 + 3.46410 - 10 - 2  R=-13.857i-2.000j  R = &radic;(-13.857)2 + (-2)2&nbsp;  \u21d2 &radic;195.988&nbsp;  \u21d2 14.0N (1dp)","marks":"10","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>8>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : PROJECTILES","question":"An object is projected vertically upwards, its height, hm, at time t seconds is given by h = 20t - 3/2t2 - 2/3t3. Find    the time at which it is momentarily at rest.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"h=20t-32t2-23t3  The body will be momentarily at rest when v = 0  v=dhdt=0  dhdt=20-2(32)t-3(23)t2  20 - 3t - 2t2 = 0  Product: -40} -8  Sum: -3} +5  20 - 8t + 5t - 2t2 = 0  4(5 - 2t) + t(5 - 2t) = 0  (4 + t)(5 - 2t) = 0  4 + t = 0 or 5 - 2t = 0  t = -4 or 5 = 2t  t=-4ort=52  t=212  Since time can't be negative, the object is momentarily at rest when t = 2 1/2 s","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>8>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : PROJECTILES","question":"An object is projected vertically upwards, its height, hm, at time t seconds is given by h = 20t - 3/2t2 - 2/3t3. Find  correct to two decimal places, the maximum height reached by the object.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"At maximum height, final velocity, v = 0  and for v = 0, t = 2 1/2s = 5/2 s  Buth=20t-32t2-23t3  h=20(52)-32(52)2-23(52)3  h=50-758-12512  h = 50 - 9.375 - 10.417  h = 30.208m  h \u2248 30.21m [2dp]","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>9>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : POLYNOMIAL FUNCTIONS","question":"The roots of the equation x2 + mx + 11 = 0 are \u03b1 and \u03b2, where m is a constant. If \u03b12 + \u03b22 = 27, find the values of m.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"x2 + mx + 11 = 0 is a quadratic equation whose roots are \u03b1 and \u03b2.  \u03b12 + \u03b22 = 27  Recall,  (\u03b1 + \u03b2)2 = (\u03b1 + \u03b2)(\u03b1 + \u03b2)  (\u03b1 + \u03b2)2 = \u03b12 + \u03b1\u03b2 + \u03b1\u03b2 + \u03b22  (\u03b1 + \u03b2)2 = \u03b12 + 2\u03b1\u03b2 + \u03b22  (\u03b1 + \u03b2)2 - 2\u03b1\u03b2 = \u03b12 + \u03b22  \u2234 \u03b12 + \u03b22 = (\u03b1 + \u03b2)2 - 2\u03b1\u03b2  (\u03b1 + \u03b2)2 - 2\u03b1\u03b2 = 27  Recall;  \u03b1+\u03b2=-ba;\u03b1\u03b2=ca  From x2 + mx + 11 = 0  a = 1, b = m, c = 11  \u2234\u03b1+\u03b2=-m1=-m  \u03b1\u03b2=111=11    Therefore, (-m)2 - 2(11) = 27  m2 - 22 = 27  m2 = 27 + 22  m2 = 49  m = &radic;49&nbsp;  m = \u00b1 7  \u2234 m = 7 or -7","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>9>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : CO-ORDINATE GEOMETRY OF CONIC SECTIONS","question":"The line 2x + 3y = 1 intersects the circle 2x2 + 2y2 + 4x + 9y - 9 = 0 at points P and Q where Q lies in the fourth quadrant. Find the coordinates of P and Q.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"2x + 3y = 1 . . . (i)  2x2 + 2y2 + 4x + 9y - 9 = 0 . . . (ii)  Since the line intersects the circle, they will have the same co-ordinate at the point of their intersection. Hence, both will be solved simultaneously to get these co-ordinates.  From (i) 3y = 1 - 2x  y=1 - 2x3---------------(iii)  substitutey=1 - 2x3intoequation(ii)  2x2+2(1 - 2x3)2+4x+9(1 - 2x3)-9=0  2x2+2(1 - 2x)(1 - 2x)9+4x+(9 - 18x3)-9=0  multiply through by 9  18x2 + 2(1 - 2x - 2x + 4x2) + 36x + 3(9 - 18x) - 81 = 0  18x2 + 2 - 8x + 8x2 +36x + 27 - 54x - 81 = 0  26x2 - 26x - 52 = 0  Divide through by 26  x2 - x - 2 = 0  Product: -2} -2  Sum: -1} +1  x2 + x - 2x - 2 = 0  x(x + 1) - 2(x + 1) = 0  (x + 1)(x - 2) = 0  x - 2 = 0 or x + 1 = 0  x = 2 or x = -1  x = 2 or -1  Recall;  y=1 - 2x3  when x = 2  y=1 - 2(2)3  y=1 - 43  y=-33  y = -1    When x = -1  y=1 - 2(-1)3  y=1 + 23  y=33  y = 1    when x = 2, y = -1 and when x = -1, y = 1  Since Q lies in the fourth quadrant, the co-ordinate of Q is (+x, -y) from the sketch below:      Hence, the co-ordinates are P(-1, 1) and Q(2, -1)","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>10>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : SURDS","question":"Solve the equation &radic;4x - 3&nbsp; - &radic;2x - 5&nbsp; = 2.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"&radic;4x - 3&nbsp; - &radic;2x - 5&nbsp; = 2  It is simpler transferring one of the terms with root to the RHS. The aim is to remove the root  &radic;4x - 3&nbsp; = &radic;2x - 5&nbsp; + 2  square both sides  (&radic;4x - 3&nbsp;)2 = (&radic;2x - 5&nbsp; + 2)2  4x - 3 = (&radic;2x - 5&nbsp;)2 + 2&radic;2x - 5&nbsp; + 2&radic;2x - 5&nbsp; + 4  4x - 3 = 2x - 5 + 4&radic;2x - 5&nbsp; + 4  4x - 2x - 3 + 5 - 4 = 4&radic;2x - 5&nbsp;  2x - 2 = 4&radic;2x - 5&nbsp;  2(x - 1) = 4&radic;2x - 5&nbsp;  x - 1 = 2&radic;2x - 5&nbsp;  square both sides  (x - 1)2 = (2&radic;2x - 5&nbsp;)2  (x - 1)(x - 1) = 4(2x - 5)  x2 - x - x + 1 = 8x - 20  x2 - 2x - 8x + 1 + 20 = 0  x2 - 10x + 21 = 0  Product: +21} -7  Sum: -10} -3  x2 - 7x - 3x + 21 = 0  x(x - 7) - 3(x - 7) = 0  (x - 3)(x - 7) = 0  x - 3 = 0 or x - 7 = 0  x = 3 or 7","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>10>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : CO-ORDINATE GEOMETRY OF CONIC SECTIONS","question":"Find the finite area enclosed by the curve y2 = 4x and the line y + x = 0.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Since the line y + x = 0 and the curve y2 = 4x intersect, the x-coordinate of their meeting points can be determined by solving the equations of the line and curve simultaneously.  y + x = 0 ........ (i)  y2 = 4x ....... (ii)  From (i)  y = -x ........... (iii)  substitute y = -x into (ii)  (-x)2 = 4x  x2 - 4x = 0  x(x - 4) = 0  x = 0 or x - 4 = 0  x = 0 or 4    From (1); y = -x; From (ii) y2 = 4x  Area = \u222b40 y2dx - \u222b40 y dx  \u222b40 4xdx - \u222b40 -xdx  \u222b40 [4x - (x)]dx  \u222b40 (4x + x)dx  \u222b40 5xdx  Integrate:  5x2/2 |40  =5(4)22-5(0)22  =5 \u00d7 162-0  \u21d2 40 - 0  \u21d2 40","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>11>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : MATRICES AND DETERMINANTS","question":"Giventhat52-3-1k639(k+2)=-207  find the values of the constant k.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"+-+52-3-1k639(k+2)=-207  +5k69(k+2)-2-163(k+2)+(-3)-1k39=-207  5[k(k + 2) - 9(6)] - 2[-1(k + 2) - 6(3)] - 3[-1(9) - 3k] = -207  5[k2 + 2k - 54] - 2[-k - 2 - 18] -3[-9 - 3k] = -207  5k2 + 10k - 270 + 2k + 4 + 36 + 27 + 9k = -207  5k2 + 21 + 4 = 0  Product: 20} +20  Sum: 21} +1  5k2 + 20k + k + 4 = 0  5k(k + 4) + 1(k + 4) = 0  (5k + 1)(k + 4) = 0  5k + 1 = 0 or k + 4 = 0  5k = -1 or k = -4  k=-15or-4","marks":"2.5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>11>b>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : DIFFERENTIATION","question":"The equation of a curve is x(y2 + 1) - y(x2 + 1) + 4 = 0.  Find the    gradient of the curve at any point (x, y).","images":[],"marking_scheme":"x(y2 + 1) - y(x2 + 1) + 4 = 0    Gradient is the derivative of the function.  xy2 + x - x2y - y + 4 = 0  Since x and y are together, this is an implicit differentiation. Where x and y are together, it will be differentiated using product rule. Anytime y is differentiated, dy/dx must be included.    (1)y2+x(2y)dydx+1-2xy-x2dydx-dydx=0  2xydydx-x2dydx-dydx=2xy-1-y2  dydx(2xy-x2-1)=2xy-1-y2  dydx=2xy - 1 - y22xy - x2 - 1","marks":"2.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>11>b>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : DIFFERENTIATION","question":"The equation of a curve is x(y2 + 1) - y(x2 + 1) + 4 = 0.  Find the   equation of the tangent to the curve at the point (-1, -3).","images":[],"marking_scheme":"At (-1, -3), the tangent and the curve the same gradient i.e mt = mc  mt = gradient of tangent  mc = gradient of curve  dydx=mt=mc=2(-1)(-3) - 1 - (-3)22(-1)(-3) - (-1)2-1  =6 - 1 - 96 - 1 - 1  =-44  \u21d2 -1  Equation of a line (tangent) which passes through (-1, -3)  Recall,  Equationofaline,m=y - y1x - x1  -1=y-(-3)x-(-1)  -1=y + 3x + 1  -1(x + 1) = y + 3  -x - 1 = y + 3  0 = y - x + 3 + 1  y - x + 4 = 0","marks":"2.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>12>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : APPLICATIONS OF THE DEFINITE INTEGRAL","question":"Using the trapezium rule with seven ordinates, evaluate \u222b30dxx2+1, correct to two decimal places.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"\u222b30dxx2+1withsevenordinates  i.e x should have seven values.  x  x2  x2 + 1  y = 1/x2+10.0  0.00  1.00  1.00000.5  0.25  1.25  0.80001.0  1.00  2.00  0.50001.5  2.25  3.25  0.30772.0  4.00  5.00  0.20002.5  6.25  7.25  0.13793.0  9.00  10.00  0.1000      Area = Area of trapezia APQB, BQRC, CRSD, DSTE, ETUF and FUVG  Recall that;  AreaofTrapezium=12(a+b)h  where a and b are the parallel sides.  Area=12(1.000+0.8000)0.5+12(0.8000+0.5000)0.5+12(0.5000+0.3077)0.5+12(0.3077+0.2000)0.5+12(0.2000+0.1379)0.5+12(0.1379+0.1000)0.5  =12(1.8000)0.5+12(1.3000)0.5+12(0.8077)0.5+12(0.5077)0.5+12(0.3379)0.5+12(0.2379)0.5  \u21d2 0.4500 + 0.3250 + 0.2019 + 0.1269 + 0.0845 + 0.0595  \u2234 A = 1.2478  \u222b30dxx2+1=1.25 (2dp)","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>12>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : MATRICES AND DETERMINANTS","question":"Using matrix method, solve -2x + y = 3; -x + 4y = 1","images":[],"marking_scheme":"-2x + y = 3  -x + 4y = 1  -21-14xy=31  A X = Y  A=-21-14  X=xy  Y=31  X = A-1Y  whereA-1=1A.AdjA  A=-21-14  \u21d2 (-2 \u00d7 4) - (-1 \u00d7 1)  \u21d2 -8 - (-1)  \u21d2 -7    Adj. A is the transpose of its co-factor  Let P be the co-factor of matrix A.    Firstly, assign sign to the element positions.  P=+P11-P12-P21+P22  For P11, cancel row 1 and column 1 of matrix A and write what is left and that is 4.  For P12, cancel row 1 and column 2 of matrix A and write what is left and that -1, and so on.  P=+4-(-1)-1+(-2)  P=41)-1-2  Adj. A is transpose of P i.e PT  PT=4-11-2  Adj.A=4-11-2  A-1=-174-11-2  -4/7+1/7-1/7+2/7  A-1Y=-4/7+1/7-1/7+2/731  -3( 4/7 ) + +1/7 (1)-3( 1/7 ) + -2/7(1)  = -11/7-1/7  xy=-11/7-1/7   x=-117,y=-17","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>13>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"If 18Cr = 18Cr + 2, find rC5.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"18Cr = 18Cr + 2  18!(18 - r)!r!=18!(18 - (r + 2))!(r + 2)!  (18 - r - 2)!(r + 2)! = (18 - r)!r!  (16 - r)!(r + 2)! = (18 - r)!r!  (16 - r)!(r + 2)(r + 2 - 1)(r + 2 - 2)! = (18 - r)(18 - r - 1)(18 - r - 2)!r!  (16 - r)!(r + 2)(r + 1)(r!) = (18 - r)(17 - r)(16 - r)!r!  (r + 2)(r + 1) = (18 - r)(17 - r)  r2 + r + 2r + 2 = 306 - 18r - 17r + r2  3r + 2 = 306 - 35r  3r + 35r = 306 - 2  38r = 304  r=30438  r = 8    rC5 = ? but r = 8  8C5=8!(8 - 5)!5!  =8!3!5!  =8 x 7 x 6 x 5!3 x 2 x 1 x 5!  \u21d2 56","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>13>b>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"In a community, 10% of the people tested positive to the HIV virus. If 6 persons from the community are selected at random, one after the other with replacement, calculate correct to four decimal places, the probability that    exactly 5.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"P=10%=10100=110  P=110  q=1-110=910(Thosenottestedpositive)    r = 5, n = 6  Recall,  P(r) = nCrPrqn - r  P(5)=6C5(110)5(910)6-5  =6!(6 - 5)!5!(0.1)5(0.9)1  6 \u00d7 5!1!5!(0.1)5(0.9)1  6 \u00d7 5!1!5!\u00d70.00001\u00d70.9  \u21d2 6 \u00d7 0.00001 \u00d7 0.9  \u21d2 0.000054  \u21d2 0.0001 [4.d.p]","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>13>b>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"In a community, 10% of the people tested positive to the HIV virus. If 6 persons from the community are selected at random, one after the other with replacement, calculate correct to four decimal places, the probability that  none","images":[],"marking_scheme":"r = 0, n = 6  Recall,  P(r) = nCr Prqn - r  P(0)=6C0(110)0(910)6-0  =6!(6-0)!0!(1)(910)6  6!6!(1)(0.9)6  \u21d2 0.531441  \u2248 0.5314 [4dp]","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>13>b>iii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"In a community, 10% of the people tested positive to the HIV virus. If 6 persons from the community are selected at random, one after the other with replacement, calculate correct to four decimal places, the probability that  at most 2; tested positive to the virus.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"at most 2 means it can be less than 2  r = 2, r = 1, r = 0  P(r \u2264 2) = P(0) + P(1) + Pr(2)  = 6C0(0.1)0(0.9)6 + 6C1(0.1)1(0.9)5 + 6C2(0.1)2(0.9)4  =0.5314+6!(6-1)!1!(0.9)5(0.1)+6!(6-2)!2!(0.1)2(0.9)4  =0.5314+6 \u00d7 5!5!(0.9)5(0.1)+6 \u00d7 5 \u00d7 4!4!2!(0.1)2(0.9)4  \u21d2 0.5314 + 0.354292 + 0.098415  \u21d2 0.984107  \u21d2 0.9841 [4dp]","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>14>a>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"The table shows the distribution of ages of workers in a company.  Age (in years)17 - 2122 - 2627 - 3132 - 3637 - 4142 - 4647 - 5152 - 56No. of workers122430374525107  Using an assumed mean of 39, calculate the    mean","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Assume mean, x\u0305a = 39  Age in yearsNumber of workers (f)Midpoint (x)d = x - x\u0305ad2fdfd217 - 21  21 - 26  27 - 31  32 - 36  37 - 41  42 - 46  47 - 51  52 - 5612  24  30  37  45  25  10  719  24  29  34  39  44  49  54-20  -15  -10  -5  0  5  10  15400  225  100  25  0  25  100  225-240  -360  -300  -185  0  125  100  1054800  5400  300  925  0  625  100  1575190-75517,325    mean,x\u0305=x\u0305a+\u2211fd\u2211f  =39+(-755)190  \u21d2 39 - 3.974  x\u0305 = 35.04","marks":"2.5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>14>a>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"The table shows the distribution of ages of workers in a company.  Age (in years)17 - 2122 - 2627 - 3132 - 3637 - 4142 - 4647 - 5152 - 56No. of workers122430374525107  Using an assumed mean of 39, calculate the  standard deviation, of the distribution.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Standarddeviation,S.D=&radic;\u2211fd2n-(\u2211fdn)2&nbsp;  =&radic;17325190-(-755190)2&nbsp;  \u21d2 &radic;91.184 - (-3.974)2&nbsp;  \u21d2 &radic;75.392&nbsp; = 8.68","marks":"2.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>14>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"If a worker is selected at random from the company for an award, what is the probability that he is at most 36 years old?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"At most 36 means 36 or below  Total number of workers, = 190  At most 36 years = 12 + 24 + 30 + 37 = 103  Pr(Atmst36years)=103190=0.542","marks":"5","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>15>a>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : CORRELATION AND REGRESSION","question":"The table shows the marks obtained by some candidates in Physics (y) and Mathematics (x) tests.  Mathematics43464839306084540Physics545363304475203349    Represent this information on a scatter diagram.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Mathematics43464839306084540Physics545363304475203349    Title: A graph of y against x  Scale: Let 2cm represent 10unit on y-axis  Let 2cm represent 10 unit on x-axis","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>15>a>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"The table shows the marks obtained by some candidates in Physics (y) and Mathematics (x) tests.  Mathematics43464839306084540Physics545363304475203349  Find x\u0305 and y\u0305, the mean of x and y respectively","images":[],"marking_scheme":"x\u0305=\u2211xn=43 + 46 + 48 + 39 + 30 + 60 + 8 + 45 + 409    =3599=39.9  y\u0305=\u2211yn=54+53+63+30+44+75+20+33+499  =4219=46.8  (x\u0305, y\u0305) = (39.9, 46.8)","marks":"1.5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>15>a>iii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : CORRELATION AND REGRESSION","question":"The table shows the marks obtained by some candidates in Physics (y) and Mathematics (x) tests.  Mathematics43464839306084540Physics545363304475203349  Draw the line of best fit to pass through (x\u0305, y\u0305).","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Title: A graph of y against x  Scale: Let 2cm represent 10unit on y-axis  Let 2cm represent 10 unit on x-axis","marks":"1.5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>15>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : CORRELATION AND REGRESSION","question":"The table shows the marks obtained by some candidates in Physics (y) and Mathematics (x) tests.  Mathematics43464839306084540Physics545363304475203349    Find the equation of the line in (a)(iii).","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Equation of the line in (a)(iii) above  Recall,  y - y\u0305 = a1(x - x\u0305)  where,a1=\u2211xy - Nx\u0305y\u0305\u2211x2 - Nx\u03052  Construct a table to determine xy and x2  xyxyx243  46  48  39  30  60  8  45  4054  53  63  30  44  75  20  33  492322  2438  3024  1170  1320  4500  160  1485  19601849  2116  2304  1521  900  3600  64  2025  160018,37915,979  a=18,379 - (9 \u00d7 39.9 \u00d7 46.8)15979 - (9 \u00d7 39.9 \u00d7 39.9)  a=1573.121650.91  a1 = 0.95  y - 46.8 = 0.95(x - 39.9)  y - 46.8 = 0.95x - 37.905  y - 0.95x = 8.895  y = 0.95x + 8.90","marks":"1.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>15>c","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : CORRELATION AND REGRESSION","question":"Use your equation in (b) to find, correct to one decimal place, the mark in Physics for a candidate who scored 28 in Mathematics.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"28 in Mathematics i.e x = 28  y = 0.95 \u00d7 28 + 8.90  y = 26.6 + 8.90  y = 35.5 [1.dp]","marks":"1.5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>16>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : TRIGONOMETRY","question":"Find, correct to one decimal place the angle between  p=3-1andq=34","images":[],"marking_scheme":"p=3-1andq=34  Recall,  cos\u03b8=p.q/p/ /q/  p = 3i - j, q = 3i + 4j  p.q = (3i - j) . (3i + 4j)  \u21d2 (3 \u00d7 3) + (-1 \u00d7 4) = 9 - 4  \u21d2 5  |p| = &radic;32 + (-1)2&nbsp;  \u21d2 &radic;9 + 1&nbsp;  \u21d2 &radic;10&nbsp;    |q| = &radic;32 + 42&nbsp;  \u21d2 &radic;9 + 16&nbsp;  \u21d2 &radic;25&nbsp; = 5  cos\u03b8=5&radic;10&nbsp; \u00d7 5  cos\u03b8=1&radic;10&nbsp;  cos\u03b8 = 0.3162  \u03b8 = cos-10.3162  \u03b8 = 71.6\u00b0 [1dp]","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>16>b>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : STATICS","question":"ABCD is a square with vertices at A(0, 0), B(2, 0), C(2, 2) and D(0, 2), Forces of magnitudes 10N, 15N, 20N and 5N act along BA.BC, DC and AD respectively. Find the    magnitude.","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"5N and 15N are like vectors. Their resultant is (5 + 15)N northward.  20N and 10N are unlike vectors. Their resultant is (20 - 10)N eastward.      Using Pythagoras' theorem  R2 = 202 + 102  R2 = 400 + 100  R2 = 500  R = &radic;500&nbsp;  R = 22.36N  From trigonometric ratio,  tan\u03b8=2010  tan\u03b8 = 2  \u03b8 = tan-12  \u03b8 = 63.4\u00b0","marks":"2.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>16>b>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : STATICS","question":"ABCD is a square with vertices at A(0, 0), B(2, 0), C(2, 2) and D(0, 2), Forces of magnitudes 10N, 15N, 20N and 5N act along BA.BC, DC and AD respectively. Find the   direction; of their resultant.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The resultant force 22.36N acts in the north east direction making angle 63.4\u00b0 with the positive x-axis.","marks":"2.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>17","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"17","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : STATICS","question":"A body of mass 20kg is suspended at point A by two inextensible strings to points X and Y, where |AX| = 1.7m, |AY| = 2.1m and |XY| = 2.9m. If the body remains in equilibrium, calculate, correct to significant figures, the tension in each string.  [Take g = 10ms-2]","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Using Cosine rule  2.92 = 1.72 + 2.12 - 2(1.7)(2.1)cos\u03b8  cos\u03b8=1.72 + 2.12 - 2.922(1.7)(2.1)  cos\u03b8 = -0.1555  \u03b8 = cos-1(-0.1555)  \u03b8 = 98.95\u00b0      Using sine rule  2.9sin98.5=1.7sin\u03b1  sin\u03b1=1.7sin98.52.9  sin\u03b1 = 0.5798  \u03b1 = sin-10.5798  \u03b1 = 35.4\u00b0    Using Lami's theorem  200sin98.5=T1sin125.4  T1=200sin125.4sin98.5  T1 = 165N  \u03b2 + 90 + 98.5 + 125.4 = 360 (sum of angles at a point)  \u03b2 = 360 - 90 - 98.5 - 125.4  \u03b2 = 46.1    Using Lami's theorem  200sin98.5=T2sin136.1  T2=200sin136.1sin98.5  T2 = 140N","marks":"10","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>18>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : VECTORS","question":"The position vectors of points P, Q and R are; 2i + j, i + kj and 3i + 2j respectively, where k is a constant. If the area of triangle PQR is 4 square units, find the value of k.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"OP = 2i - j  OQ = 1 + kj  OR = 3i + 2j     AreaoftrianglePQR=12+-+2-111k1321  12(2(k-2)-(-1)(1-3)+1(2-3k))  12(2k-4-2+2-3k)  12(-k - 4)  But the area is 4 square units  12(-k-4)=4  -k - 4 = 8  -k = 8 + 4  -k = 12  k = -12","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>18>b>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : THE CONCEPTS OF MOTION","question":"A train moving along a straight track accelerates uniformly from rest at 300mh-2. When its speed reaches 100kmh-1, it moves with that velocity for 40 minutes. It then decelerates uniformly to a stop in 20 minutes.    Sketch the velocity time graph for the journey.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"1.5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>18>b>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : THE CONCEPTS OF MOTION","question":"A train moving along a straight track accelerates uniformly from rest at 300mh-2. When its speed reaches 100kmh-1, it moves with that velocity for 40 minutes. It then decelerates uniformly to a stop in 20 minutes.  Determine the magnitude of the retardation.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Retardation takes place in the last stage of motion.  u = 100km/h, v = 0m/s,   t=20min=2060=13hr  retardation, a = ?  Recall,  v = u + at  0=100+a(13)  -100=a3  -300 = a  a = -300m/h2  The negative sign shows a negative acceleration i.e retardation.","marks":"1.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>18>b>iii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : THE CONCEPTS OF MOTION","question":"A train moving along a straight track accelerates uniformly from rest at 300mh-2. When its speed reaches 100kmh-1, it moves with that velocity for 40 minutes. It then decelerates uniformly to a stop in 20 minutes.  Find the total distance covered by train.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"From the first stage of the motion i.e acceleration stage.  u = 0km/h, v = 100km/h, a = 300km/h2, t = ?  Recall,  v = u + at  100 = 0 + 300(t1)  100 = 300t1  t1=100300  t1=13hr  Totaltime=13+4060+2060  13+23+13  1 + 2 + 13  =43hrs  Total Distance, D is the area under the graph i.e area of a trapezium.  D=12(a+b)h  D=12(43+23)100  =12\u00d763\u00d7100  \u21d2 100km","marks":"1.5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2007>18>b>iv","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2007","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iv","group":"","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : THE CONCEPTS OF MOTION","question":"A train moving along a straight track accelerates uniformly from rest at 300mh-2. When its speed reaches 100kmh-1, it moves with that velocity for 40 minutes. It then decelerates uniformly to a stop in 20 minutes.  What is the total time it travelled before stopping?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Totaltime,t=43hrs=113hrs=1hr20min","marks":"1.5","difficulty":"2"}];